tter''' (born May 1, 1953) is the [[U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|Colorado|7|}}, serving since 2007. The district is located in the northwestern suburbs of [[Denver]]. He is a member of the [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party]].\n\n==Early life, education and career==\nPerlmutter was born in Denver, the son of Alice Love (n\u00e9e Bristow) and Leonard Michael Perlmutter. His father was Jewish, the son of immigrants from Ukraine; his mother was Christian, and was of English and Irish descent.<ref>http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/reps/perlmutter.htm</ref> Perlmutter describes himself as a [[Christian]].<ref name=0825golb/><ref name=oo>{{cite web|title=Ed Perlmutter|publisher=Facebook|year=2010|url=https://www.facebook.com/Ed4Colorado|accessdate=2010-12-20}}</ref><ref name=\"blogs.jta.org\">http://blogs.jta.org/politics/article/2009/05/28/1005498/in-the-senate-still-13-tribesmen</ref> Perlmutter graduated from [[Jefferson High School (Edgewater, Colorado)|Jefferson High School]] in [[Edgewater, Colorado]] and went on to study political science, history and economics at the [[University of Colorado at Boulder]], graduating in 1975. He received his [[Juris Doctor]] from CU in 1978 where he was twice elected President of his class while working part time as a laborer on construction projects.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\nPerlmutter was formerly a director of the law firm of Berenbaum Weinshienk, and specialized in business reorganizations and commercial litigation.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\n==Colorado Senate==\nPerlmutter was a Colorado State Senator from 1995 to 2003. He was elected to two four-year terms to represent central [[Jefferson County, Colorado|Jefferson County]] as State Senator from 1995 to 2003\u2014the first Democrat elected in the district in 30 years.\n\nIn 2000, he helped lead a team that succeeded in a Democratic takeover of the Colorado State Senate for the first time since [[John F. Kennedy]] was president. He has assisted numerous campaigns and most recently was co-chair of the [[John Kerry|Kerry Campaign]] in [[Colorado]].\n\nIn the Colorado Senate, he served on numerous [[Colorado State Senate]] committees including: Water, Finance, Judiciary, Child Welfare, Telecommunication, Transportation, Legal Services, and Oil and Gas.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Financial Services|Committee on Financial Services]]'''\n** [[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Capital Markets, Insurance, and Government-Sponsored Enterprises|Subcommittee on Capital Markets, Insurance, and Government-Sponsored Enterprises]]\n\n==Political campaigns==\n\n===2006===\n{{Main|Colorado 7th congressional district election, 2006}}\nPerlmutter won the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nomination for the 7th District by defeating former State Representative [[Peggy Lamm]] and college professor [[Herb Rubenstein]], with 53% of the vote in the primary. State education chairman [[Rick O'Donnell]] was unopposed for the Republican nomination. [[Dave Chandler]], a Green, was also a candidate.\n\nThe seat was held by Republican [[Bob Beauprez]], who was reelected to a second term in [[U.S. House elections, 2004|2004]] with 55% of the vote, after winning his first term by only 121 votes. He left the seat at the end of the 2004\u20132006 term, having failed in his bid to become [[Governor of Colorado]].\n\nIn late September, O'Donnell was put on the defensive when ads appeared noting that he had previously supported abolishing Social Security. A Survey USA poll soon after that showed Perlmutter with a 54 to 37 percent lead, although GOP consultants guessed that the support was \"soft\".<ref>[http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/elections/article/0,2808,DRMN_24736_5024085,00.html ]{{Dead link|date=July 2010}}</ref> An October 4 poll released by Zogby showed Perlmutter ahead of O'Donnell by 45-34 percent.<ref>{{cite news|title=Results in key House races: Reuters poll|agency=Reuters|date=2006-10-04|work=Washington Post|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/10/04/AR2006100400310.html}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref> ''Cook Political Report'' rating: ''Republican Toss Up''. ''CQPolitics'' rating: ''No Clear Favorite''.\n\nIn the end, Perlmutter (54%) soundly defeated O'Donnell (42%) for the congressional seat, helping Democrats to regain the majority in the U.S. House.\n\n===2008===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Colorado, 2008#District 7}}\nPerlmutter won against Republican nominee [[John W. Lerew]].{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}\n\n===2010===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Colorado, 2010#District 7}}\nPerlmutter defeated Republican nominee [[Ryan Frazier]] and Libertarian nominee Buck Bailey on November 2, 2010. The 7th Congressional district had been cited as a GOP target in 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/09/us/politics/09colorado.html|title=Democrats See Hopes for West Dim in Colorado|last=Zeleny|first=Roger|date=2010-05-09|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=10 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n===2012===\nPerlmutter defeated Republican nominee [[Joe Coors Jr.]] on November 6, 2012. Perlmutter's victory came despite new congressional boundaries that made his district 4 percent less Democratic.  Perlmutter was ahead by 9 percentage points in Jefferson County, where 60 percent of the voters live.  Perlmutter led Coors by 17 percentage points in Adams County, where 40 percent of the constituents in the newly drawn 7th District live.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.denverpost.com/ci_21941755/neighbors-perlmutter-coors-square-off-new-7th-district|title=Perlmutter wins fourth term, Coors tapped out in 7th district|last=Bartels|first=Lynn|date=2012-06-11|publisher=Denver Post|accessdate=7 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPerlmutter has three children. He and his first wife, Deana, divorced in 2008. In November 2010, Perlmutter married Nancy Henderson.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/thespot/2010/11/25/perlmutters-getting-married-on-friday/18965/|title=Perlmutters getting married on Friday|date=2010-11-25|publisher=Denver Post}}</ref>\nNancy Perlmutter teaches mathematics at Pomona High School and has three adult children.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://perlmutter.house.gov/ U.S. Congressman Ed Perlmutter] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.perlmutterforcolorado.com Perlmutter for Colorado] official campaign site\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Colorado/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Ed_Perlmutter_%5BD-7%5D}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = p000593 | ballot = Ed_Perlmutter | nndb = 063/000122694 | votesmart = 2653 | govtrack = 412192 | opencong = 412192_Ed_Perlmutter | rollcall = 25518 | politifact = | fec = H6CO07023 | opensecrets = N00027510 | assets = ed-perlmutter | legistorm = 857/Rep_Edwin_George_Perlmutter.html | followthemoney = 18040 | ontheissues = House/Ed_Perlmutter.htm | congress = ed-perlmutter/1835 | worldcat = | cspan = 1021382 | imdb = | bloomberg = | nyt = | washpo = gIQAyxjSAP }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| state=Colorado\n| district=7\n| before=[[Bob Beauprez]]\n| start=January 3, 2007}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jerry McNerney]]<br><small>D-[[California]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=213th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Peter Roskam]]<br><small>R-[[Illinois]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{CO-FedRep}}\n\n{{Persondata <!-- Metadata: see [[Wikipedia:Persondata]]. -->\n|NAME              = Perlmutter, Ed\n|ALTERNATIVE NAMES =\n|SHORT DESCRIPTION = American politician\n|DATE OF BIRTH     = 1953-05-01\n|